deck: The place that is not a place, where forgotten characters reside and nothing happens at all.
description:
Limbo is a place of the forgotten, where all outdated comic book characters go: the forgotten, the unpopular, the silly ones, those who no longer appeal to readers' tastes. It is where all objects and people lost to the revision of continuity end up.

One enters Limbo when they are forgotten, but once they leave, they never remember having been there. And if you stay, your own memory will soon fail you.

Seen for first time in Animal Man, the geography of the Limbo includes a library with only one book, an infinite book where all stories are being depicted.

When Superman, Ultraman, Overman, Captain Atom and Captain Marvel travelled through the multiverse, they found themselves stranded in Limbo. There they participated againts a shadow demons attack with the help of Limbo inhabitants.

In the map of the multiverse, limbo can be seen in several positions above the sphere of the gods.
name: Limbo (of comics)

volume_credits.name: Scribblenauts Unmasked: A Crisis of Imagination

deck: Where millions of dreamers go every hour. It's a place where people go to relive their pasts, or imagine their future, or when they're missing something from their lives and don't know how to let go. Everyone coming to the Dreamscape needs to know it's a safe place - that's when the Dream Police comes in.
description:
People in the Dreamscape:

  • Dreamers (see also Echoes)
    • Regular Dreamers
    • Recurrent Dreamers (e.g. Mary James)
    • Augmented and lucid dreamers (mostly high on drugs)
    • Nightwalkers
  • Dead Souls (the Shades)
  • Residents
    • Dream Police (e.g. Joe Thursday, Katie Black, Frank Stafford, Captain Ross)
    • Supervisors
    • The Elders
    • Changelings
    • Wisps
    • The Architects
    • Nightmares
  • Other Beings
    • Aliens
    • Dragons

Places in the Dreamscape:

The Dreamscape is a ever-shifting place being constantly and instantly designed and re-designed by the Architects based on the imagination of dreamers - even in their wildest dreams. Some places, though, are always there, somewhere:

  • DPD / Dream Police Department's Headquarters
    • The Black Files (guarded by Zek, the file-guardian, and his dogs, the biters)
    • The Recruitment Office (where Dex Dilby works)
  • Mirrors - a Shifter's bar and main transit point.
  • Shifty's - a diner; sometimes Italian, Mexican, or Indian.
  • The Routing Center - where freshly arrived Dreamers are given their fantasies and dreams.
  • The Loop - where all the recurrent dreams are sent to.
  • The Darkness - a cold infinite structure at the outer edge and without light.
  • The Verge - a vast place beyond the "Zone of Shared Perception" where nobody dares to go and will (probably) never come back from. At the end of the Verge is the wall that separates the Dreamscape from the "waking world".
name: Dreamscape

deck: Theme park of Angor. It was the last vestige of that civilization.
description:
Wacky World was a thematic park in the world of Angor. It was the last remains of that world's civilization. It was built by Mitch Wacky, a technological genius, who created a race of thinking robots.

When the super villains group the Extremists caused a nuclear apocalypse in Angor than killed all the people, the park and its robots survived and continued upgrading themselves, perplexed by the absent of human visitors. They also built a cult around his creator. Under the directive to be more wacky, the robots created new attractions than resembled the dead heroes and villains from their world. The copies were so similar then they ended fighting for real, with the androids believing themselves the real deal. The triumphant robotic super villains left the park under the control of Carny and ventured beyond its limits. The real nature of the park was revealed when the Justice League Europe found themselves stranded in Angor threatened to be forever entertained until death.

Originally, it was also a spoof of the Disneyland theme park, including the urban legend of Walt Disney being cryogenically frozen under the park.
